00:01:05.390 --> 00:01:23.760
Amy Kate Bordenave: So, the TDEI Walksheds tool calculates pedestrian walk shed areas around a specified origin point. A walkshed is the region reachable by pedestrians on foot or by mobility device within a given travel time or cost budget.

11
00:01:23.810 --> 00:01:33.050
Amy Kate Bordenave: Given the characteristics of the surrounding pedestrian network, that means sidewalks, crossings, slopes, and barriers such as curbs and stairs.

12
00:01:33.720 --> 00:01:51.639
Amy Kate Bordenave: Unlike a simple distance radius, which used to be the way that people computed walksheds, a walk shed reflects real-world travel conditions, so two points equidistant from an origin may have very different costs to reach, depending on

13
00:01:51.640 --> 00:02:02.320
Amy Kate Bordenave: The slope of the segments, whether there's any raised curbs or stairs, or whether the route requires crossing a busy street versus a quiet neighborhood one.

14
00:02:02.550 --> 00:02:09.140
Amy Kate Bordenave: The result is a realistic map of accessible space from a chosen origin point.

15
00:02:10.389 --> 00:02:13.169
